==Demography==
Wellingborough's population expanded rapidly from 26,000 to 60,000 in the 1960s and 1970s as agreements were signed between the Urban District Council and [[London County Council]] and the [[Greater London Council]] for the town to re-house over-spill population from London. Following the post [[World War II]] arrival of immigrants from the Commonwealth group of nations into Britain, a sizeable [[Black Caribbean]] and [[demographics of India|Indian]]/[[Pakistani]] community grew up in this small market town, and now represents  7% of the population in the Borough and to 11% within the town.<ref name="wellingborough.gov.uk">[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/info/349/business_advice/249/invest_in_wellingborough/6 The Borough Council of Wellingborough: Population] Retrieved 23 August 2009</ref>

==Economy==
[[Image:Northampton 6.04.2008 008.jpg|thumb|right|The Swansgate Shopping Centre in 2008]]
Wellingborough has approximately 2,500 registered businesses within its boundaries.<ref>[http://www.connectedwellingborough.co.uk/opportunities Connected Wellingborough: Opportunities] Retrieved 12 June 2010</ref> Much of the town centre was redeveloped during the 1970s, when it grew rapidly from London overspill. The [[Wellingborough (borough)|Borough Council]] has adopted a 'Town Centre Action Plan'.<ref>[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=525&pageNumber=6  Growth in Wellingborough] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> The former traditional economic structure based on footwear and engineering is gradually diversifying with wholesale, logistics, and service sectors providing new opportunities for employment.

As a market town, Wellingborough has major high street chains mainly located in the town centre. The only shopping centre, Swansgate,<ref>[http://www.swansgateshoppingcentre.com/index.php Swansgate Shopping Centre] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> previously known as the [[Arndale Centre]], was built in the late 1970s. Since 2009 the Borough Council has been looking at rebuilding the centre<ref name="TC Mplan">[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/site/scripts/google_results.php?q=Rebuilding+swansgate+ The Borough Council of Wellingborough: Rebuilding Swansgate] Retrieved: 20 April 2010</ref> and major stores want bigger floor-spaces.<ref>[http://www.northantset.co.uk/news/Bignames-too-large-for-town.5817565.jp Northants Evening Telegraph: Big-names too large for town] Retrieved 30 January 2010</ref> Supplementing the town centre shops are several out-of-town retail parks and supermarkets including a [[Sainsbury's]],<ref>[http://www.sainsburys.co.uk/sol/storelocator/storelocator_landing.jsp;SOLSESSIONID=LkkVSpJwzRG2hRrcKktqtJx2QQrZSCqKZpTYcCQpc2HttPMfWBT1!1195600802!91706513?bmForm=stores_main_search&bmFormID=1264854197539&bmUID=1264854197539&bmIsForm=true&bmPrevTemplate=%2Fsol%2Fstorelocator%2Fstorelocator_landing.jsp&bmText=search_string_field&search_string_field=Wellingborough&bmHidden=notifysearchcontroller&notifysearchcontroller=fromsrchmechnsm&bmSubmit=Go&bmHidden=isJavascriptEnabled&isJavascriptEnabled=true&redirectto=mapView Sainsbury's: Wellingborough Store] Retrieved 30 January 2010</ref> four [[Tesco|Tesco's]]<ref>[http://www.tesco.com/storelocator/ Tesco: Store Locator] Retrieved 30 January 2010</ref> stores, an [[Aldi]]<ref>[http://yellowmap.de/filialfinder/HTML/Info.aspx?Ebinr=HVE5A47253FJG93&SessionGuid=7179fb5a-0a80-470e-a757-77a6de6a4b4c&ClearGroups=MapNav%2cGeoMap&ClearParas=Print&DetailInfoView=2 Aldi: Wellingborough store] Retrieved 30 January 2010</ref> store and a [[Morrisons]]<ref>[http://www.morrisons.co.uk/Store-Finder/Store-Details/?type=qs&value=Wellingborough&recordid=1&lat=52.30103&lon=-0.69590 Morrisons: Wellingborough store] Retrieved 30 Jaunary 2010]</ref> store in the town centre. The town has a market three times a week and a weekly privately organised market.<ref name="Wellingborough Market"/>

Other businesses operating within the town include motorsport, high performance engineering, distribution, environmental technology and renewable energy, digital and  creative media, financial and business services, and global brands. There are several industrial estates in the town, these include Park Farm,<ref>[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=108&pageNumber=4 Borough Council of Wellingborough: Park Farm industrial estate] Retrieved 30 January 2010</ref> Denington,<ref>[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=108&pageNumber=3 Borough Council of Wellingborough: Denington industrial estate] Retrieved 30 January 2010</ref> Layland<ref>[http://www.whittlejones.com/investment-details.php?tsubid=29&regcode=mid Whittle Jones: Layland trading estate] Retrieved 30 January 2010</ref> and Finedon Road.<ref>[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/info/677/property_enquiries/108/land_and_property/4#pagenavbox Borough Council of Wellingborough: Finedon Road industrial estate] Retrieved 30 January 2010</ref>
;Future developments

As part of its Milton Keynes [[South Midlands]] (MKSM) study, the government has identified Wellingborough as one of several towns in Northamptonshire into which growth will be directed over the next thirty years. It allocates 12,800 additional homes to Wellingborough, and will also create additional facilities, further improve the town centre, improve infrastructure and increase employment opportunities. A jobs growth target of 12,400 jobs has been set to accompany the large scale housing growth.<ref name="NNDC">[http://www.nndev.co.uk/ North Northants Development Company] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> A plan for 3,000 homes north of the town has been accepted by the UK Government after an appeal by Bee Bee Developments. The plan was first refused by Wellingborough Borough Council.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cleaver |first=Monique |title=Green light for 3,000 new homes |date=11 February 2010  |url=http://www.northantset.co.uk/wellingborough/Green-light-for-3000-new.6103406.jp |publisher=''Northants Evening Telegraph'' |accessdate=25 February 2010}}</ref>

As a result, plans have been made for a major urban extension in the town, mainly to the east of the railway station. When finished, the town would be around 30% larger and 3,200 new homes would be built on 'Stanton Cross' site, with new Schools, Bus stops, Community Centres, Shops, a Doctor's surgery, and new open spaces.<ref>[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/downloads/Housing_Strategy200912.pdf The Borough Council of Wellingborough Housing  Strategy (PDF)] Retrieved 23 August 2009</ref>
The [[Wellingborough railway station|railway station]] would be developed into an 'interchange' with [[Stagecoach in Northants|local buses]] and [[East Midlands Trains|trains]]. The upgrade would provide a new platform, footbridge and new station buildings.<ref name="Station">[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/downloads/file/3491/growth_area_development_fact_sheet-may_2009 The Borough Council of Wellingborough: Growth Area Development May 2009] Retrieved 20 April 2010</ref> Outside the station a new road bridge from Midland Road over the railway line is also planned with a new footbridge to reach the new development.<ref>[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/downloads/file/2162/growth_area_fact_sheet-november_2007 The Borough Council of Wellingborough: Growth Area Fact Sheet 2007] Retrieved 20 April 2010</ref> Other plans to include the development of the High Street, Shelley Road and the north of the town areas are also being considered.<ref>[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?documentID=525&pageNumber=1 Wellingborough planning] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wellingborough 2020 Vision: A strategy for regeneration and growth in Wellingborough |publisher=Borough Council of Wellingborough |format=PDF |url=http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/download/4254/2020_vision Wellingborough 2020 Vision |accessdate=20 April 2010}}</ref>

==Transport==
The [[A45 road|A45 dual carriageway]] skirting to the south, links the town with the [[A14 road (England)|A14]], and [[M1 motorway|M1]] which also allows links  to the east and west of the country. The A45 links Wellingborough with [[Northampton]], [[Rushden]], [[Higham Ferrers]], [[Raunds]], [[Thrapston]], [[Oundle]] and [[Peterborough]].
[[Image:Wellingboroughstationbuilding.jpg|right|thumb|Wellingborough station building]]
The town is served by a bus network provided by [[Stagecoach in Northants]] and [[First Northampton]], with local Connect Wellingborough buses W1, W2, W3, W4, W5, W6, W7, and  W8 linking the town centre (Church Street) with local suburbs and villages.<ref name="Stagecoach Northants">[http://www.stagecoachbus.com/uploads/wellimapdownloadlo.pdf Stagecoach in Northants Connect Wellingborough Network] Retrieved 21 March 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.firstgroup.com/ukbus/eastmidlands/northampton/timetables/index.php?operator=20&page=1&redirect=no First Northampton] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> The route 23 is a local commuter bus from the town centre to Park Farm Industry Estate and route 24 between Kettering and Wellingborough is a local bus for the Redwell area.<ref name="Stagecoach Northants"/>
Departing every 30 minutes the X4 service also links the town with [[Milton Keynes]], Northampton, Kettering, [[Corby]], Oundle and Peterborough.<ref>[http://www.stagecoachbus.com/northamptonshire-X4.aspx Stagecoach Northants X4] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> Other routes include 38, 45 and X46.<ref name="Stagecoach Northants"/>

[[East Midlands Trains]] operate direct trains to [[St Pancras railway station|London St Pancras International]] from [[Wellingborough railway station]], departing every 30 minutes, with an average journey time of around 55 minutes.<ref name="EMT">[http://eastmidlandstrains.co.uk/NR/rdonlyres/A563C19B-07D3-42D6-A6CF-5B14526ECB20/0/Route1TimetableDec09.pdf East Midlands Trains: Midland Main Line Timetable] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> The railway line also connects Wellingborough with [[Bedford]], [[Luton]], [[Kettering]], [[Corby]], [[Leicester]], [[Nottingham]], [[Derby]], [[Sheffield]] and [[Leeds]]. 

Several UK airports are within two hours' drive of the town, including [[London Luton Airport|London Luton]], [[East Midlands Airport|East Midlands]], [[Birmingham International Airport (United Kingdom)|Birmingham International]] and [[London Stansted Airport|London Stansted]]. Luton can be reached directly by train while East Midlands and Stansted can be reached by one change at Leicester. [[Sywell Aerodrome]], located 5 miles northwest of Wellingborough, caters for [[general aviation|private flying]], [[flight training]] and corporate flights.

==Education==
{{See|List of schools in Northamptonshire}}
Fourteen government controlled primary schools feed the secondary schools that include:
[[Wellingborough School]], an independent, fee-paying school with a [[Wellingborough School CCF|cadet force]], and the state secondary schools of [[Sir Christopher Hatton School]], [[Weavers School]], [[Wrenn School]] (formerly the Wellingborough Grammar School), and Friars School.<ref name="schools">[http://www2.northamptonshire.gov.uk/findmynearest/FindMyNearestMap.aspx?feature=schools_all&x=489590.59&y=268056.06 Northampton County Council: Map of Schools] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref>

The [[Tresham College of Further and Higher Education]] has a main campus in Wellingborough, and outreach  locations in [[Kettering]], [[Oakham]] and [[Corby]].<ref>[http://www.tresham.ac.uk/about/our_campuses Tresham College: Our Campuses]. Retrieved 8 August 2009</ref> It provides [[further education]] and offers vocational courses, [[GCSE]]s and [[GCE Advanced Level in the United Kingdom|A Level]]s.<ref>[http://www.tresham.ac.uk/courses Tresham College: Our Courses]. Retrieved 8 August 2009</ref>  In collaboration with several universities the college also offers Higher Education options.<ref>[http://www.tresham.ac.uk/higher_education Tresham College: Higher Education]. Retrieved 8 August 2009</ref>

The [[University of Northampton]] in [[Northampton]], with  around 10,000 students on two campuses, offers courses from foundation and undergraduate levels to postgraduate, professional and doctoral qualifications. Subjects include traditional arts, humanities and sciences subjects, as well as entrepreneurship, product design and advertising.<ref>[http://www.northampton.ac.uk/about/ The University of Northampton: About Us]. Retrieved 8 August 2009</ref>
==Culture==
[[Image:The Castle - geograph.org.uk - 27294.jpg|thumb|right|The Castle Theatre]]
''[[The Castle Theatre, Wellingborough|The Castle Theatre]]'' was opened in 1995 on the site of Wellingborough's old Cattle Market.<ref>[http://www.thecastle.org.uk/aboutus/history/ Castle Theatre: History] Retrieved 21 March 2010</ref> It brings not only a theatre to the area but other facilities for local people. Most rooms are used on a daily basis by the local community, users include the Castle Youth Theatre<ref>[http://www.thecastle.org.uk/participate/youththeatre/ Castle Theatre: Youth theatre] Retrieved 2 March 2010</ref> and Youth  Dance.<ref>[http://www.thecastle.org.uk/participate/youthdance/ Castle Theatre: Youth dance] Retrieved 2 March 2010</ref>

Wellingborough has a public library in the corner of the market square.<ref>[http://www.northamptonshire.gov.uk/en/councilservices/Leisure/Libraries/publib/Pages/Wellib.aspx Northamptonshire County Council: Wellingborough Library] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> The Wellingborough Museum,<ref>[http://www.wellingboroughmuseum.co.uk/ Wellingborough Museum's website] Retrieved 19 June 2010</ref> located  next door to ''The Castle Theatre'', has exhibitions which show the past of Wellingborough and the surrounding villages.  Accompanying the exhibitions and articles is a souvenir shop.<ref>[http://www.culture24.org.uk/em000061 Wellingborough Museum entry on Culture24] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref>

==Sport==
Wellingborough is home to two football clubs: [[Wellingborough Town F.C.|Wellingborough Town]]<ref>[http://www.wellingboroughtownfc.co.uk/ Wellingborough Town F.C.] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> and [[Wellingborough Whitworth F.C.|Wellingborough Whitworth]].<ref>[http://www.clubwebsite.co.uk/whitworthfc/ Wellingborough Whitworth] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref>  In 2009 the town's rugby  club  was the first club to be awarded the RFU Whole Club Seal of Approval in the [[East Midlands]].<ref>[http://www.wrfc.net/content/view/404/187/ Wellingborough Rugby Football Club] Retrieved 14 January</ref>  [[Great Harrowden#Great Harrowden Hall|Harrowden Hall]], a 17th century building in [[Great Harrowden]] village just on the outskirts of the town, is the clubhouse of a privately  owned golf course.<ref>[http://www.wellingboroughgolfclub.org/ Wellingborough Golf Club] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> The five leisure centres and health clubs in  Wellingborough include [[Bannatyne's]], Club Diana,<ref>[http://www.theclubdiana.co.uk Club Diana Wellingborough] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> Redwell, and Waendel and Weavers (which is part of Weavers school).<ref>[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/site/scripts/documents_info.php?categoryID=1490&documentID=73 The Borough Council of Wellingborough: Leisure centres] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref>

==Services==
Several [[National Health Service|NHS]] centres provide health care facilities, with Isebrook Hospital being equipped for procedures such  as large X-Rays and neurological investigations, and long-term care, that are not  catered for by  primary  care surgeries. Accident & Emergency (A&E), maternity,<ref>[http://www.nhs.uk/ServiceDirectories/Pages/MaternityDetails.aspx?id=MT135 NHS: Maternity Details] Retrieved 28 January 2010</ref> and surgical issues are mainly covered by [[Kettering General Hospital]]. [[Air Ambulance]] is provided by Warkshire and Northamptonshire Air Ambulance service.<ref>[http://www.wnaa.co.uk/ Warkshire and Northamptonshire Air Ambulance] Retrieved 2 March 2010</ref> A petition signed by thousands of local residents in the towns of Wellingborough and Rushden for a new A&E to be built in Wellingborough has been handed to [[10 Downing Street]] (when Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] was in power), by local MP [[Peter Bone]] on 10 February 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goodjohn |first=Bernie |title=Petition handed over for hospital |url=http://www.northantset.co.uk/wellingborough/Petition-handed-over-for-hospital.6058445.jp |date=10 February 2010 |publisher=''Northants Evening Telegraph''  |accessdate= 16 February 2010}}</ref>

Other emergency services are provided by the [[Northamptonshire Fire and Rescue Service]] and the [[Northamptonshire Police]]. The [[Wellingborough (HM Prison)|HM Prison Wellingborough]] is located just outside the town.

==Landmarks==
[[File:Three_silver_ladies.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Sculpture: ''Three Silver Ladies''.]] 
The railway  station  is a Grade II Listed building, and among  the many unusual  and other listed buildings in  Wellingborough  is the the 600 year old Grade I listed steeple  that  is all that  remains of All Hallows Church.''The Three Silver Ladies'' is one of two identical sculptures installed on the  Harrowden Road, They  depict  local Roman history, the river, and the  the townspeople working together.<ref>[http://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/599501 Geograph] retrieved 24 June 2010</ref>

==Notable Wellingburians==
[[Image:David Frost Rumsfeld interview cropped.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Sir David Frost attended Wellingborough Grammar School.]]
Wellingborough is the birthplace and residence of many notable people, including the former world champion snooker player [[Peter Ebdon]], and Sir [[David Frost]], [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], a broadcaster who attended Wellingborough Grammar School, whose campus is now occupied by the [[Wrenn School]].<ref>Tall, David & Graham (2006) ''Memories of Wellingborough Grammar School'' [http://www.wgsmemories.org.uk/book/ Foreword by  Sir David Frost]. </ref> The winner of [[Britain's Strongest Man]] contest in 2002, [[Marc Iliffe]], lives in the town.

Scientist [[Kenneth Mees]], and [[Frederic Henry Gravely]] an [[arachnologist]], [[entomologist]], and [[zoologist]] were born in the town. [[Paul Pindar]], an ambassador of [[King James I of England|King James I]] to the [[Ottoman Empire]], was born and grew up in the town, and attended [[Wellingborough School]].

The town has sports people such as [[Rory McLeod (snooker player)|Rory McLeod]] and<ref>[http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/others/snooker-why-am-i-the-only-black-pro-on-circuit-1863150.html The Independent] Retrieved 24 February 2010</ref> [[Jamie O'Neill (snooker player)|Jamie O'Neill]] both snooker players, born in the town,<ref>[http://www.globalcuesportscentre.com/globalsnookercentre/files/Players/Global_Europe/Global_England/eng_jamie_oneill.htm Global Snooker Centre] Retrieved 25 February 2010</ref>
and football  players [[Trevor Benjamin]]<ref>[http://www.northantset.co.uk/local-football-gossip/Transfer-talk--deadline-day.5585528.jp Northants Evening Telegraph: Transfer Talk] Retrieved 25 February 2010</ref> and [[Bill Perkins (footballer)|Bill Perkins]] both grew up in the town. Perkins played for a number of teams including [[Liverpool Football Club]], [[Kettering Town]] and [[Northampton Town]].<ref>[http://www.lfchistory.net/player_profile.asp?player_id=798 IFC History:Bill Perkins] Retrieved 25 February 2010</ref> [[Fanny Walden]] was born in the town, formerly playing for Northampton Town and [[Tottenham Hotspur]]. [[Brian Hill (referee)|Brian Hill]], referee,  was also born in the town.<ref>[http://www.rushdenheritage.co.uk/commerce/Hill-Brian-Marriotts.html Rushden Heritage] Retrieved 25 February 2010</ref>

Wellingborough is home to singers [[Peter John Murphy|Peter Murphy]] of [[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]] who lived a large portion of his early life in here, and [[Thom Yorke]] of [[Radiohead]],  and politicians [[Alfred Dobbs]], [[Arthur Allen (Labour politician)|Arthur Allen]] (for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]) and [[Brian Binley]] (for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]) were all born in the town.

Authors connected with the town include [[Lesley Glaister]] who was born in Wellingborough, while [[Stephen Elboz]] was born and currently lives in the town.<ref>[http://www.oup.com/oxed/children/authors/elboz/ Oxford University Press: Stephen Elboz] Retrieved 25 February 2010</ref> Journalist and whisky writer [[Jim Murray (writer)|Jim Murray]] also lives here. Author and historian [[Bruce Quarrie]] formally lived in the town before his death in 2004. A school in Wellingborough is named after Sir [[Christopher Hatton]], and [[Edward Mannock]] is mentioned on the Wellingborough [[War Memorial]].

==Twin towns==
Wellingborough is [[town twinning|twinned]] with:
*{{flagicon|France}} [[Niort]], [[France]] (1977) <ref name="twin">[http://www.wellingborough.gov.uk/site/scripts/google_results.php?q=twin++town Town twinning.] Retrieved 17 June 2010</ref>
*{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Wittlich]], [[Germany]].<ref name="twin"/>
and also  has relations with [[Willingboro]], township in [[Burlington County]], [[New Jersey]], USA,<ref name="twin"/> while Irchester and Grendon, two  of the villages within the Borough of Wellingborough, have twin town partners at Coulon near Niort, and Bois-Bernard near Arras.<ref name="twin"/>

